  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3114282403" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3114282403" />
    <a title="Çağrı" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/80892063-a-r"><img alt="Çağrı" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1642015217p2/80892063.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3114282403?book_show_action=true">Jan 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Çağrı" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Çağrı" href="/user/show/80892063-a-r">Çağrı</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/80892063-a-r?shelf=history_read">history_read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3114282403" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13765572393539537751">This text covers a lot of ground in political thought. From the definition of natural law, to autonomy, to property rights and firstly should be read by anyone who is interested in this field of history or politics. However, the fact that the context of Locke’s writing is in such a tumultuous and exciting period of British history, makes it an even more fascinating read for me, and I would recommend others who are interested in this period to give this book a read. <br/><br/>Whilst Locke’s true intention </span>
  <span id="freeText13765572393539537751" style="display:none">This text covers a lot of ground in political thought. From the definition of natural law, to autonomy, to property rights and firstly should be read by anyone who is interested in this field of history or politics. However, the fact that the context of Locke’s writing is in such a tumultuous and exciting period of British history, makes it an even more fascinating read for me, and I would recommend others who are interested in this period to give this book a read. <br /><br />Whilst Locke’s true intention for writing could be questioned, as it always can be in any political text, it seems that this text is highly influenced by Locke’s personal anti-monarchy stance whilst also trying to present an authentic political philosophy. John Locke is writing at a time when Charles II has been restored following a series of civil wars in Britain. Largely influenced also by his close friend Ashley Cooper who later becomes Earl of Shaftesbury and leader of the radical Whig opposition, Locke adopts a strong anti-monarchy, anti-absolutist (both monarchical and religious) stance. Ultimately, it can also be seen as a subtle way of calling for a revolution, to remove the newly restored monarch from power. <br /><br />This text can also be more meaningful if read with prior knowledge about Thomas Hobbes’ thesis, outlined in most detail in the ‘Leviathan’. Interestingly, Locke argues directly against Hobbes’ fundamental premise. Hobbes argues that within humans’ natural state, they are actually not properly free. We are weak and uncivilised; if we don’t establish some form of contract, then we would just fight each other due to everyone being on their own quest for fulfilling their urges. By contrast, Locke is arguing that the basic state of nature ensures a fundamental human right to freedom, and also argues that we are better off in that state than being a slave under an absolute monarch. As creations of God, we have the individual power to uphold laws of nature and this is what makes us sovereign. <br /><br />Similarly, Locke’s method for understanding the nature of a state - its power, origin and so on - also involves discerning a law of nature. Locke argues that the law of nature is something that reason dictates but which God is the basis (or provider) of - hence atheists or Catholics cannot be tolerated. It is something that everybody is bound by and dictates that we have a duty, and therefore right, for self-preservation. But, in the circumstances, we also have a duty to preserve and help others. This means that, for example, other people’s property cannot be stolen. That said, he does argue that property ultimately comes from God and that we are commanded by Him to make use of these - references are made to ‘go forth and multiply’. Everyone also has a right to persecute those who transgress against the laws of nature. To make this more efficient in a more populated environment such as a state, a civil state would have appointed people responsible for passing judgements on and settling disputes. People would therefore have a (crucial) right to appeal if there is a dispute about property. Hence, Locke argues against absolute monarchies and does not believe that they can be defined as civil. In such systems, there is no one other than the one, supreme holder of power to whom you can make a dispute.<br /><br />Therefore, because of our right to uphold our autonomy in natural law, we also have the right to overthrow any illegitimate leader who is not fulfilling their duty to uphold this in their society. If power is not being used to maintain the interest of the people, the trust is broken. Even if the trust that people hold in their sovereign appears to have been violated, the bond is broken and the power of parliament is broken. Every individual has a right to judge when and how this trust is broken and then to fight against such a person and take the power for themselves whilst ‘appealing to heaven’. This part is what explicitly shows a kind of theory building up to an advocacy for revolution. <br /><br />Seeing as the slogan of the Whigs was ‘liberty and property’ strong ties can easily be seen between them and Locke. Whilst it would be anachronistic, Locke could certainly be seen as a liberal of his time. Seeing the explicit arguments that justify a resistance to Charles II’s government makes this text worth a read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13765572393539537751" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

