<div id="review_3224036686" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3224036686" />
    <a title="Jonathan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62545863-jonathan"><img alt="Jonathan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553527919p2/62545863.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3224036686?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan" href="/user/show/62545863-jonathan">Jonathan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/62545863-jonathan?shelf=read-since-11-15-16">read-since-11-15-16</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/62545863-jonathan?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3224036686" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6046013559282662194">7/10<br/><br/>&quot;The main end of government is the protection of property.&quot;<br/><br/>In this book, Locke gives two treatise on government, this first as a response to Robert Filmers argument for the divine right of kings, and the second, to set up how he believes governance comes about, and what its limits are. <br/><br/>The first Treatise<br/>Essentially Locke dismantles any semblance of argument for the divine right of kings by interacting directly with Filmer (who he appears to genuinely dislike), and interpreting the same passa</span>
  <span id="freeText6046013559282662194" style="display:none">7/10<br /><br />"The main end of government is the protection of property."<br /><br />In this book, Locke gives two treatise on government, this first as a response to Robert Filmers argument for the divine right of kings, and the second, to set up how he believes governance comes about, and what its limits are. <br /><br />The first Treatise<br />Essentially Locke dismantles any semblance of argument for the divine right of kings by interacting directly with Filmer (who he appears to genuinely dislike), and interpreting the same passage of the Bible that Filmer had used, to show where Filmer had erred. Filmer continually conflates fatherhood with kingship, that's his whole argument. As such, he sees no need for the consent of the governed to the governor. Honestly in hindsight, this arguement is rather dull as its difficult to find anyone who still agrees with Filmer. That is in large part due to Locke however, lest we forget. <br /><br />Personally, I've been thinking about the Biblical continual rejection of the firstborn in favor of the younger. We see after Cain a passing of the birthright to the younger, this can be seen with Jacob, Joseph, Judah, Moses, David and Solomon. I could go so far as to say that being the firstborn was actually a negative indicator biblically when it came to leadership. <br /><br />“Methinks Sir Robert should have carried his Monarchical Power one step higher and satisfied the World, that Princes might eat their Subjects too.”<br /><br />The second Treatise<br />Locke believes that in pre-governmental life (The state of nature), man has unlimited liberty, but not the license to infringe upon the liberty of another. We were not made for the use of one another, but the earth was made for our use. All the earth is our common property, but labor creates ownership. If I till a field or catch a fish, I, by virtue of my work, have removed the goods from the common ownership and transferred them to my soul ownership. As much as I agree with Locke on this point, I have to say this is a relatively weak absolute argument. This is probably why we have to "Take these truths as self-evident."<br /><br />Nature is ruled by reason. Forgoing reason is therefore breaking the law of nature. Laws our enforced by reason, but carried out by the right of punishment, which Locke believes is carried by all, not only the injured party, in order to insure no one else is harmed by the criminal. <br />As you grow in reason, so you grow in self-governance. <br /><br />"Every man is born with two rights, the right to his own life, and the right to his inheritance from his father."<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6046013559282662194" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


