        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2783327779" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12221641233345410309">Two Treatises of Government<br/>By: John Locke<br/><br/> “Slavery is so vile and miserable an estate of man, and so directly opposite to the generous temper and courage of our nation, that it is hardly to be conceived that an Englishman, much less a gentleman, should plead for it.” Revolutionary words proclaimed by whom that is conceived in great intelligence and liberal thought. Two Treatises of Government is an essay regarding problematic issues that contradicted the welfare of England’s populace at the time</span>
  <span id="freeText12221641233345410309" style="display:none">Two Treatises of Government<br />By: John Locke<br /><br /> “Slavery is so vile and miserable an estate of man, and so directly opposite to the generous temper and courage of our nation, that it is hardly to be conceived that an Englishman, much less a gentleman, should plead for it.” Revolutionary words proclaimed by whom that is conceived in great intelligence and liberal thought. Two Treatises of Government is an essay regarding problematic issues that contradicted the welfare of England’s populace at the time, that being the sixteen-nineties. Such topics being that of slavery, consciousness and acknowledgment of its malevolence around a century and a half before the propagation of such ideas are expressed; such other ideas as natural rights and their inalienable and must applicability to all members of society is also addressed. The first predominant focus of the essay regards “Filmer’s Theory”, specifically, its discredibility and the fallacies of the theory. Robert Filmer created the theory that Adam from the story of Adam and Eve, has absolute ruling power from death and forward to control governments and that power would be inherited by male offspring and that power was bestowed and protected by Providence; Robert was also thought poorly of democracies and the will of the people. Much of what Locke states is seen in other significant documents such as the U.S Declaration of Independence; both political documents contest the right of rule by a monarch with fictitious power given by God and certain rights that are given by God to all.<br /><br />his book has multiple factors to determine who would most enjoy it and its political philosophy. I would recommend Two Treatises of Government to anyone wishing to advance their historical knowledge and understanding of Western politics and the political beliefs of the time; especially somebody wishing to have an occupation in political science. Those who do not engage in politics could also find the contents of the book interesting for its archaic wording and terminology as that could be used to develop their own. <br /><br /> <br /><br /> <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12221641233345410309" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


