  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4005643542" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4005643542" />
    <a title="Fraser Kinnear" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3030419-fraser-kinnear"><img alt="Fraser Kinnear" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1260502319p2/3030419.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4005643542?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fraser Kinnear" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fraser Kinnear" href="/user/show/3030419-fraser-kinnear">Fraser Kinnear</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3030419-fraser-kinnear?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3030419-fraser-kinnear?shelf=politics">politics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4005643542" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15674181023340726592">The First Treatise is mostly dunking on somebody who argued for hereditary monarchies, especially those claiming divine Christian rights. <br/><br/>The Second Treatise was a sensible response in anticipation of Filmer’s challenge to come up with a better theory to justify political power. My book was very nicely organized by Section, which I reference below.<br/><br/>Broadly, Locke’s response goes that men are all born free, and originally lived in a State of Nature (S. 104). They chose to form governments (S. 119)</span>
  <span id="freeText15674181023340726592" style="display:none">The First Treatise is mostly dunking on somebody who argued for hereditary monarchies, especially those claiming divine Christian rights. <br /><br />The Second Treatise was a sensible response in anticipation of Filmer’s challenge to come up with a better theory to justify political power. My book was very nicely organized by Section, which I reference below.<br /><br />Broadly, Locke’s response goes that men are all born free, and originally lived in a State of Nature (S. 104). They chose to form governments (S. 119) (with later generations implicitly consenting to join governments) in the interest of protecting their property (S. 124). Practically, this meant sacrificing certain powers (S 128-130), including giving government a monopoly over violence. The government in part protected property because it treats everyone the same (S. 136) (a partial realization of Rule of Law). <br /><br />To be well maintained, government requires direct participation by everyone (S. 143) (or perhaps just property owners, not sure). But participation doesn’t mean complete management, and Lock explains the necessity of an executive to implement laws chosen by a legislative (S. 159). <br /><br />Both the legislative and the executive can abuse their powers (S. 155), but Locke argues that this is a form of tyranny (S. 201-202), and a populous has the right to replace this government, as necessary (S. 221-222). <br /><br />Nothing terribly surprising, and therefore nothing very interesting. Perhaps one interesting thought was that Locke identified the risk of having <i>too good</i> of an executive (Prince), because it leaves an unwary populous who may be easily tricked by the next executive (S. 166). I also really appreciated Locke’s anti-Girardian opinion that one can’t inherit their parents’ mistakes (S. 182). <br /><br />Makes me wonder how awful life must have been in the late 1600’s that this book was only published anonymously, and Locke didn’t admit authorship until his deathbed.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15674181023340726592" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

